	abstract = {Using a stochastic approximation procedure \${\textbackslash}\{X\_n{\textbackslash}\}, n = 1, 2, {\textbackslash}cdots\$, for a value \${\textbackslash}theta\$, it seems likely that frequent fluctuations in the sign of \$(X\_n - {\textbackslash}theta) - (X\_\{n - 1\} - {\textbackslash}theta) = X\_n - X\_\{n - 1\}\$ indicate that \${\textbar}X\_n - {\textbackslash}theta{\textbar}\$ is small, whereas few fluctuations in the sign of \$X\_n - X\_\{n - 1\}\$ indicate that \$X\_n\$ is still far away from \${\textbackslash}theta\$. In view of this, certain approximation procedures are considered, for which the magnitude of the \$n\$th step (i.e., \$X\_\{n + 1\} - X\_n\$) depends on the number of changes in sign in \$(X\_i - X\_\{i - 1\})\$ for \$i = 2, {\textbackslash}cdots, n\$. In theorems 2 and 3, \$\$X\_\{n + 1\} - X\_n\$\$ is of the form \$b\_nZ\_n\$, where \$Z\_n\$ is a random variable whose conditional expectation, given \$X\_1, {\textbackslash}cdots, X\_n\$, has the opposite sign of \$X\_n - {\textbackslash}theta\$ and \$b\_n\$ is a positive real number. \$b\_n\$ depends in our processes on the changes in sign of \$\$X\_i - X\_\{i - 1\}(i {\textbackslash}leqq n)\$\$ in such a way that more changes in sign give a smaller \$b\_n\$. Thus the smaller the number of changes in sign before the \$n\$th step, the larger we make the correction on \$X\_n\$ at the \$n\$th step. These procedures may accelerate the convergence of \$X\_n\$ to \${\textbackslash}theta\$, when compared to the usual procedures ([3] and [5]). The result that the considered procedures converge with probability one may be useful for finding optimal procedures. Application to the Robbins-Monro procedure (Theorem 2) seems more interesting than application to the Kiefer-Wolfowitz procedure (Theorem 3).},
