	doi = {10.1037/0278-7393.11.3.579},
	abstract = {Investigated the role of color in the recognition and naming of everyday objects in 3 studies with 77 undergraduate and graduate students and 75 20–35 yr old medical students, nurses, and doctors. In Exp I, the effect of color on object naming and the influence of relevant shape information on color naming were studied; geometric shapes for which a simple name was readily available and random nonsense shapes were also compared. Results show that color pictures were named faster than black-and-white and that shape information did not facilitate color naming. Exp II attempted to determine the stage of object processing at which the color facilitation occurred. It was found that color had no effect on object recognition but did facilitate object naming, even when color was redundant for discrimination. This did not apply to naming abstract shapes. Exp III replicated the findings of Exp II using different objects and colors. Findings show that color could facilitate but not inhibit object naming and did not affect object recognition. It is suggested that color can facilitate but not interfere with object naming. (37 ref)},
